      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Property During Separation or Divorce in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When a relationship ends and a jointly owned property needs to be sold, the legal framework and practical realities are different from a standard sale. Here is what you need to know.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a property during separation or divorce involves layers that a straightforward sale does not: two parties who may not be communicating well, legal processes running alongside the real estate process, financial outcomes that need to be agreed or ordered by a court, and a significant amount of personal stress on both sides. Understanding how these pieces interact helps you manage the sale process effectively and avoid the complications that arise when the legal and real estate tracks are not coordinated.</p>

      <p>This article is not legal advice. If you are going through a separation or divorce and need to sell jointly owned property, you need a family lawyer. What follows is a practical overview of how the property sale process works in this context, and what an experienced agent can and cannot do to help.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework: family law and property ownership</h2>
      <p>In Australia, property settlement after separation is governed by the Family Law Act 1975, which applies to both married couples and de facto partners. The legislation gives the Family Court of Australia and the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia broad powers to make orders about property, including orders requiring the sale of jointly owned real estate and directing how the proceeds are to be distributed.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, residential property is commonly owned in one of two ways: as joint tenants (where both owners hold equal shares and the right of survivorship applies) or as tenants in common (where each owner holds a specific share that can be different from the other's and can be dealt with independently). For a jointly owned property to be sold, both owners typically need to execute the contract of sale. Neither owner can unilaterally sell a jointly owned property without the other's signature or a court order authorising the sale.</p>

      <p>If both parties agree to sell and can cooperate on the basics of the campaign, the sale process runs close to normally. The complications arise when one party wants to sell and the other does not, or when there is disagreement about the price, the choice of agent, the timing, or how the proceeds should be distributed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When one party wants to sell and the other does not</h2>
      <p>If agreement on a sale cannot be reached, the party who wants to sell has two main options. The first is a partition application, where the court orders the property to be sold and proceeds divided, or in some cases orders that one party buys out the other. The second is a full property settlement application, which resolves the broader financial relationship between the parties and typically includes an order about the family home as part of a larger package.</p>

      <p>Both options involve legal proceedings, take time, and incur costs. Courts generally encourage parties to reach agreement outside of litigation, and many family lawyers will advise exploring mediation or collaborative law processes before commencing court proceedings. The practical reality is that most separating couples who need to sell their home eventually do reach an agreement, even if the negotiation is difficult. Court orders are available but should be understood as a backstop, not a first resort.</p>

      <p>If you find yourself in this situation, the best step is to engage a family lawyer immediately and let them manage the legal track. An experienced agent can provide appraisals and market information that can help inform negotiations, but the decision to list should not be made until there is at least informal agreement between the parties, or a court order that authorises the sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing the sale process when parties are not cooperating</h2>
      <p>Even when both parties agree in principle to sell, managing a property campaign when the owners are not communicating directly requires careful handling by the agent. As an agent working with a separating couple, the right approach is to establish clear communication protocols from the start: who is the primary contact for which decisions, whether written communication is preferred over phone calls, and how to handle situations where the two parties give conflicting instructions.</p>

      <p>Inspections can create practical challenges if one party is still living in the property or if there is tension about access. Agreeing on an open home schedule before the campaign starts, and confirming that schedule in writing to both parties, reduces the likelihood of last-minute conflicts. If the occupying party is not cooperating with inspections, that is a legal issue that needs to be resolved before the campaign can proceed effectively, and it should be escalated to the relevant solicitors rather than managed by the agent alone.</p>

      <p>Both parties need to sign the contract of sale and any subsequent documents, including counterpart offers if negotiating through multiple parties. Delays in obtaining both signatures can frustrate buyers, so having a clear process for how and when documents will be executed should be established at the outset of the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The role of family lawyers alongside conveyancers</h2>
      <p>Selling a property in separation involves two distinct legal disciplines. Your conveyancer or property solicitor handles the contract of sale, the transfer of title, and the settlement mechanics. Your family lawyer handles the property settlement, the division of proceeds, and any court orders that are needed.</p>

      <p>These two sets of lawyers need to communicate with each other, but they have different roles and different timelines. The conveyancer needs both parties to be available to execute documents and to have clear instructions about where the net proceeds should be distributed at settlement. The family lawyer needs to ensure that the distribution of proceeds at settlement aligns with whatever agreement or court order governs the property settlement.</p>

      <p>A common source of delay is when the family law settlement has not been finalised or formally documented by the time the property contract is ready to settle. Settlement agents and solicitors cannot distribute funds in a way that contradicts a court order or a binding financial agreement, and they will hold funds in trust pending legal clarity if the position is not clear. This can be avoided by ensuring your family lawyer and your conveyancer are in communication well before the contract exchange date, and certainly before the settlement period begins.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax and the main residence exemption</h2>
      <p>The main residence CGT exemption is one of the most valuable tax concessions available to Australian homeowners. When a property that has been your main residence is sold in the context of a separation, the tax treatment can be more complex than a standard owner-occupier sale, particularly if one party has moved out before the sale occurs.</p>

      <p>The ATO provides specific concessions for former partners selling a jointly owned main residence. In many cases, both parties can access the main residence exemption even if one has already moved out, provided the sale occurs within a certain timeframe and the property was genuinely the main residence for both parties during the relevant ownership period. The rules have specific conditions and time limits that your accountant needs to assess for your specific circumstances.</p>

      <p>Do not assume that the CGT exemption applies automatically. Get advice from your accountant as early in the process as possible, not after the property has settled and the proceeds have been distributed. The timing of decisions about when to sell, how to document the sale, and how to structure the distribution of proceeds can all affect the tax outcome for both parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical steps to keep the sale moving</h2>
      <p>The property sale can often feel like it is being held hostage by the family law process, or vice versa. These are the steps that tend to keep things moving without creating additional conflict. First, agree on the agent selection together if possible, or through your lawyers if direct agreement is not practical. Having both parties comfortable with the agent removes a source of tension throughout the campaign. Second, get the appraisal done early so both parties have a realistic sense of what the property is likely to achieve. Disagreements about price expectations are common and are usually resolved more easily when there is independent, evidence-based advice on the table. Third, set up clear written communication from the start so there is a record of what has been agreed and what instructions have been given. Fourth, keep your family lawyer and your conveyancer informed of each other's timelines so that the legal and settlement processes are synchronised.</p>

      <p>Separation and divorce are difficult. The property sale, whatever its emotional significance, is ultimately a transaction with a timeline that needs to be managed. Working with an agent who understands the added complexity of these sales, and who can communicate clearly and professionally with both parties, makes a meaningful difference to how the process feels and how it concludes.</p>

